
[1]prodigality

   PRODIGAL'ITY, n.

   1. Extravagance in the expenditure of what one possesses, particularly
   of money; profusion; waste; excessive liberality. It is opposed to
   frugality, economy, and parsimony.

   By the Roman law a man of notorious prodigality was treated as non
   compos.

   The most severe censor cannot but be pleased with the prodigality of
   his wit.

   2. Profuse liberality.
